{"title_page": "Federico Russo (presenter)", "text_new": "{{Expand Italian|Federico Russo|date=April 2020}}\n{{About|the Italian presenter|the Italian actor|Federico Russo (actor)}}\n{{Infobox presenter\n|image=Trl 2005 napoli imbruglia.jpg\n|caption=Russo (right) in 2005\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1980|12|22|df=yes}}\n|birth_place=[[Florence]], [[Italy]]\n|station=[[RAI]]\n|show={{unbulleted list|''[[The Voice of Italy]]'' <small>(2014\u20132016)</small>|[[Eurovision Song Contest]] <small>(2015\u2013)</small>}}\n}}\n\n'''Federico Russo''' (born 22 December 1980) is an Italian [[Radio personality|radio]] and [[television presenter]]. He is known for presenting [[The Voice of Italy|''The Voice of Italy'']] on [[Rai 2]] (seasons 2 to 4), and for being one of the Italian commentators for the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] (since 2015).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2019/03/07/italy-federico-russo-eurovision-2019-commentator/|title=Italy: Federico Russo and Ema Stokholma Announced as Eurovision 2019 Commentators|last=Herbert|first=Emily|date=7 March 2019|website=Eurovoix|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> He was the spokesperson for Italy in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2015]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2015/04/21/italy-federico-russo-to-announce-the-points/|title=Italy: Federico Russo To Announce The Points|last=Granger|first=Anthony|date=21 April 2015|website=Eurovoix|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Italy-tv-bio-stub}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Russo, Federico}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:People from Florence]]\n[[Category:Italian television presenters]]\n[[Category:Italian radio personalities]]\n", "text_old": "{{Expand Italian|Federico Russo|date=April 2020}}\n{{About|the Italian presenter|the Italian actor|Federico Russo (actor)}}\n{{Infobox presenter\n|image=Trl 2005 napoli imbruglia.jpg\n|caption=Russo (right) in 2005\n|birth_date={{birth date and age|1980|12|22|df=yes}}\n|birth_place=[[Florence]], [[Italy]]\n|station=[[RAI]]\n|show={{unbulleted list|''[[The Voice of Italy]]'' <small>(2014\u20132016)</small>|[[Eurovision Song Contest]] <small>(2015\u2013)</small>}}\n}}\n\n'''Federico Russo''' (born 22 December 1980) is an Italian [[Radio personality|radio]] and [[television presenter]]. He is known for presenting [[The Voice of Italy|''The Voice of Italy'']] on [[Rai 2]] (seasons 2 to 4), and for being one of the Italian commentators for the [[Eurovision Song Contest]] (since 2015).<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2019/03/07/italy-federico-russo-eurovision-2019-commentator/|title=Italy: Federico Russo and Ema Stokholma Announced as Eurovision 2019 Commentators|last=Herbert|first=Emily|date=7 March 2019|website=Eurovoix|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> He was the spokesperson for Italy in the [[Eurovision Song Contest 2015]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://eurovoix.com/2015/04/21/italy-federico-russo-to-announce-the-points/|title=Italy: Federico Russo To Announce The Points|last=Granger|first=Anthony|date=21 April 2015|website=Eurovoix|language=en-GB|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}{{Italy-bio-stub}}\n{{Television-bio-stub}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Russo, Federico}}\n[[Category:1980 births]]\n[[Category:People from Florence]]\n[[Category:Italian television presenters]]\n[[Category:Italian radio personalities]]\n", "name_user": "\u00c6toms", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Federico_Russo_(presenter)"}
{"title_page": "Thiruvalla", "text_new": "\n\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Thiruvalla\n| native_name                     = <!-- Please do not add any Indic script in this infobox, per WP:INDICSCRIPT policy. -->\n| settlement_type                 = Town \n| image_skyline                   = Thiruvalla Bus Terminal Complex.jpg\n| image_alt                       =\n| image_caption                   = Thiruvalla KSRTC Bus Terminal\n| pushpin_map                     = India Kerala\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| pushpin_map_alt                 =\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Kerala, India\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Kerala]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Pathanamthitta district|Pathanamthitta]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                =\n| founder                         =\n| named_for                       =\n| government_type                 =\n| governing_body                  =\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  =\n| area_total_km2                  =\n| area_rank                       =\n| elevation_footnotes             =\n| elevation_m                     =\n| population_total                = 52,883\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_footnotes            = <ref>http://www.censusindia.gov.in/pca/SearchDetails.aspx?Id=676380</ref>\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_rank                 =\n| population_demonym              =\n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 689101\n| area_code                       = 91-469\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| registration_plate              = KL-27\n| website                         = {{URL|https://www.thiruvalla.org.in}}\n| footnotes                       =\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], [[English language|English]]\nLiteracy                  = 98.5%\n| blank2_name_sec2                = Nearest Airport\n| blank2_info_sec2                = [[Cochin International Airport Limited]]\n| official_name                   =\n}}\n\n'''Thiruvalla''', alternately spelled '''Tiruvalla''', is a small town and also the headquarters of the [[Thiruvalla taluk|Taluk of same name]] located in [[Pathanamthitta district]] in the State of [[Kerala]], [[India]]. The town is spread over an area of 27.94&nbsp;km&nbsp;.  It lies on the banks of the rivers [[Manimala River|Manimala]] and [[Pamba River|Pamba]], and is a land-locked region surrounded by irrigating streams and rivers.\n\nThiruvalla is regarded as the \"Land of Non resident Indians \".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/efforts-on-to-give-facelift-to-thiruvalla/article7998777.ece|title=Efforts on to give facelift to Thiruvalla|date=2015-12-17|newspaper=The Hindu|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref> Thiruvalla is also famous for the dance of Kathakali, which is hosted in the Sreevallabha temple almost everyday in an year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/where-kathakali-is-a-daily-affair/article3088714.ece|title=Where Kathakali is a daily affair|date=2006-08-11|work=The Hindu|access-date=2018-08-25|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nThe town spans a geographic area of 27.94&nbsp;km\u00b2 with a population of 56,828 as of 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040616075334/http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archivedate=2004-06-16|title= Census of India 2001: Data from the 2001 Census, including cities, villages and towns  (Provisional)|accessdate=2008-11-01|publisher= Census Commission of India}}</ref> Males constitute 48% of the population and females 52%. In Thiruvalla, 10% of the population is under 6 years of age. Thiruvalla has a large [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|Non-Resident Indian Community]].\n\n== Etymology ==\nOld tradition tells that the name Thiruvalla comes from the word \"''Valla Vaay''\", named after the river Manimala which was known as ''Vallay\u0101r'' in ancient times. Before roads were developed,Thiruvalla village developed at the mouth of river Vallayar,connected far and near places through waterways, hence known as ''Valla v\u0101i''(v\u0101y in old Malayalam means mouth of river).<ref name=\":0\" /> Later the Dravidian Prefix 'Thiru (means holy /revered) attached to it and became Thiruvalla.\n\nAt the time of Aryan migration to south India it became one of the 64 Brahmin settlements. They correlated the name to \"Sree Vallabha\" means Husband of Lakshmi Devi. Sree Vallabha is the presiding deity of the Thiruvalla Temple and argues that shreevallabha Puram (Land of Vallabhan) became Thiruvalla.<ref name=\":0\" /> Thiruvalla as per the Sanskrit work \"\u0936\u094d\u0930\u0940\u0935\u0932\u094d\u0932\u092d \u0915\u094d\u0937\u0947\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u092e\u093e\u0939\u093e\u0924\u094d\u092e\u094d\u092f\u092e\u094d\" (\u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40\u0d35\u0d32\u0d4d\u0d32\u0d2d \u0d15\u0d4d\u0d37\u0d47\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d30 \u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d39\u0d3e\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2e\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d02) (\u015br\u012bvallabha k\u1e63\u0113tra m\u0101h\u0101tmya\u1e41) is \"\u0936\u094d\u0930\u0940\u0935\u0932\u094d\u0932\u092d\u092a\u0941\u0930\u092e\u094d\" (\u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40\u0d35\u0d32\u0d4d\u0d32\u0d2d\u0d2a\u0d41\u0d30\u0d02)(\u015br\u012bvallabhapura\u1e41). The work is said to be of 10th century CE.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Geography and Climate ==\nThiruvalla lies at an altitude of 21 m above sea level, on the basin of the rivers [[Pamba River|Pamba]] and [[Manimala River|Manimala]]. Thiruvalla is dotted with several natural canal streams (called \"thodu\" in Malayalam) like Chanthathodu, Manippuzha, Mullelithodu, and several others. The city area has riverine alluvial soil, and eastern parts have a laterite loam kind of soil classified under \"Southern Midlands\" agro-ecological zone, while the western suburbs like Niranam have a more sandy type of soil that resembles beaches. (Kuttanad agro-ecological zone)<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kissankerala.net/kissan/kissancontents/soil.jsp#admin|title=KISSAN \u2013 Kerala|website=www.kissankerala.net|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref> The reason for this is believed to be the older status of Niranam as a port, before reclamation of Kuttanad from sea occurred. The Upper Kuttanad region in Thiruvalla has the \"Karappadam\" type of soil, which is clay loam in texture, has high organic matter, and is situated in areas about 1\u20132 m above sea level.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe climate of Thiruvalla is classified as [[Tropical climate|tropical]]. There is significant rainfall in most months of the year. The short dry season has little effect on the overall climate. The K\u00f6ppen-Geiger climate classification is Am. The temperature here averages 27.3&nbsp;\u00b0C. In a year, the average rainfall is 2975&nbsp;mm.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://en.climate-data.org/location/59916/|title=Climate: Thiruvalla - Climate graph, Temperature graph, Climate table - Climate-Data.org|website=en.climate-data.org|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box|location=Thiruvalla|metric first=yes|single line=yes|Jan high C=31.3|Feb high C=31.7|Mar high C=32.7|Apr high C=32.7|May high C=32|Jun high C=29.8|Jul high C=29.8|Aug high C=29.8|Sep high C=30|Oct high C=30|Nov high C=30|Dec high C=30.7|Jan low C=22.5|Feb low C=23.4|Mar low C=24.7|Apr low C=25.4|May low C=25|Jun low C=23.9|Jul low C=23.9|Aug low C=23.8|Sep low C=24|Oct low C=23.8|Nov low C=23.5|Dec low C=22.6|Jan precipitation mm=22|Feb precipitation mm=35|Mar precipitation mm=60|Apr precipitation mm=155|May precipitation mm=320|Jun precipitation mm=596|Jul precipitation mm=542|Aug precipitation mm=372|Sep precipitation mm=284|Oct precipitation mm=326|Nov precipitation mm=210|Dec precipitation mm=54|source=http://en.climate-data.org/location/59916|date=}}\n\nAt an average temperature of 29.0&nbsp;\u00b0C, April is the hottest month of the year. July has the lowest average temperature of the year. It is 26.4&nbsp;\u00b0C. Between the driest and wettest months, the difference in precipitation is 574&nbsp;mm. Precipitation is the lowest in January, with an average of 22&nbsp;mm. With an average of 596&nbsp;mm, the most precipitation falls in June.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nDue to proximity to the equator, Thiruvalla has very less variation in average temperature. During the year, the average temperatures vary by 2.6&nbsp;\u00b0C.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThiruvalla is best known for its pleasant and welcoming weather. South West Monsoon winds bring heavy showers to Thiruvalla in the months of August for a couple of months. Thiruvalla has a distinctively tropical, yet pleasing climate. The best time to visit this historical town is after the rains as the healthy showers of monsoon leave this place lush green and pristine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nativeplanet.com/thiruvalla/#overview|title=Thiruvalla|last=|first=|date=|website=native planet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n''This article is primarily about the history of the settlements in areas of present city around the temple, known historically as Thiruvalla. For the history of the places in Thiruvalla, also refer : [[Niranam|History of Niranam]], [[Koipuram|History of Koipuram]], [[Kumbanad|History of Kumbanad]], [[Kavumbhagom|History of Kavumbhagom]].''\n\n=== Ancient period ===\nThere is plenty of evidence to suggest that the area had been inhabited since 500 BCE, although an organized settlement was only founded around 800 CE.  The present day areas of [[Niranam]], and Kadapra on the western part of Thiruvalla were submerged under the sea before then.<ref name=\":0\" /> It is one of the 64 ancient ''brahmana graamams''.\n\nStone axes have been reported from Thiruvalla, belonging to Neolithic Age.<ref>\"Indus Civilisation and Tamil Language \u2013 Part 03\", page 34.\n\nhttp://210.212.62.26/pdf_files/books/Indus%20civilization%20and%20tamil%20language%20part%20003.pdf\n</ref> Thiruvalla has many Neolithic remains and got civilized earlier. The Aryan culture presented Thiruvalla as one of the 64 Brahmin settlements of Kerala, and one of the important too. Ptolemy mentions the Baris river, the present \"Pamba\" river.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FVsw35oEBv4C|title=A Survey Of Kerala History|last=Menon|first=A. Sreedhara|date=2007-01-01|publisher=DC Books|isbn=9788126415786|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThiruvalla was also an important commercial centre with the [[Niranam]] port in olden days, which is described by Pliny as \"[[Nelcynda]]\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SXMaAAAAMAAJ|title=Bulletin of the John Rylands Library|last=Library|first=John Rylands|date=1967-01-01|publisher=Kraus Reprint|language=en}}</ref> At this light, the \"Bacare\" could have been modern \"[[Purakkad]]\". The fact that modern western Thiruvalla contains the coastal kind of sand, and several sea shells in the soil despite being land locked proves that prior to the reclamation of Kuttanad from sea, Niranam and the whole western Thiruvalla could have been a coastal area.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== The Growth to Feudalism ===\nUp to the beginning of the 10th century CE, Ays were the dominant powers in Kerala. The Ay kings ruled from Thiruvalla in North to Nagercoil in South. Ptolemy mentions this as from Baris ([[Pamba River|Pamba river]]) to Cape Comorin \"Aioi\" ([[Kanyakumari]]).<ref name=\":1\" /> By 12th century, we get the picture from the Thiruvalla copper plates, which are voluminous records that centre around the social life around the temple.<ref name=\":1\"/> The society The Thiruvalla temple had a large Vedic learning school (actually comparable to modern university) (\"Thiruvalla salai\"), which was one of the foremost learning centres<ref name=\"Cultural Heritage of Kerala\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R7QNGkZKc5wC|title=Cultural Heritage of Kerala|date=2008-01-01|publisher=D.C. Books|isbn=9788126419036|language=en}}</ref> in Kerala. The Thiruvalla salai was one of the richest among the Vedic schools of Kerala, and according to the copper plates, the pupils of the school were fed with 350 nazhis of paddy everyday,<ref name=\"Cultural Heritage of Kerala\"/> which shows the vastness of its student population. Thiruvalla held a very eminent position among the spiritual and educational centres in ancient times.The Sri Vallabha Temple was one of the wealthiest temples of ancient Kerala, as is evident from the inscriptions in the plates. The part of the temple land required to 'feed the Brahmins' required 2.1 million litres of rice seeds, and for the \"maintenance of the eternal lamps\" required more than 340,000 litres of paddy seed capacity.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rNKGAwAAQBAJ|title=A Passage to Infinity: Medieval Indian Mathematics from Kerala and Its Impact|last=Joseph|first=George Gheverghese|date=2009-12-10|publisher=SAGE Publications India|isbn=9788132104810|language=en}}</ref> Due to the length, the antiquity and the nature of the language, Thiruvalla copper plates form the \"First book in Malayalam\", according to Prof. [[Elamkulam Kunjan Pillai|Elamkulam]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_B7jAAAAMAAJ|title=Proceedings of the Indian History Congress|last=Congress|first=Indian History|date=1970-01-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Medieval period ===\n[[File:Syrian copper plates - Kollam (c. 883 AD).jpg|thumb|Thiruvalla copper plates]]\nThe rulers of Thiruvalla now belonged to the Thekkumkoor Dynasty, which had one of its headquarters at Idathil near Kaavil Temple. Idathil (Vempolinadu Edathil Karthavu)<ref>P. Shungoonny Menon, ''A history of Travancore'' (first edition: 1878, new edition: 1983), page 130 and 131, {{ISBN|978-81-7020-040-6}}</ref> was the family name of the Thekkumkoor kings. Today's Paliakara Palace is a branch of Lakshmipuram Palace of [[Changanacherry]], which is a branch of Alikottu Kovilakam of Pazhancherry in [[Malabar (Northern Kerala)|Malabar]]. Similarly, [[Nedumpuram Palace]] is a branch of Mavelikkara Palace is an heir to the [[Kolathiri]] tradition of Udayamangalam. The Thekkumkoor kings lost their control in the course of time and Vilakkili  (\u0d35\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d3f) Nampoothiris were rulers in 1752\u201353 when [[Marthanda Varma|Anizham Thirunal Marthanda Varma]], the king of [[Travancore]], seized it in a bloody battle in which the ruler was killed, though some dispute it, saying the surrender was peaceful as the Namboothiris were not naive to challenge the mighty army of [[Ramayyan Dalawa|Ramayyan]], the shrewd and sadistic Dalava (\u0d26\u0d33\u0d35)- head of administration and advisor \u2013 of Travancore.<ref name=\":0\">Shree Vallabha Mahakshethra Charitham, P. Unnikrishnan Nair</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nThe current Chairperson of the Municipality is Cherian Polachirackal and the Vice Chairman is Sreerenjini S Pillai for 2018\u20132020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Council |url=http://www.thiruvallamunicipality.in/council |publisher=Thiruvalla Municipality |accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThiruvalla's assembly constituency is the part of the newly formed [[Pathanamthitta (Lok Sabha constituency)]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.delimitation-india.com/Final_Publications/KERALA/Final_Order_Kerala.pdf\n|format=PDF| title = ORDER NO. 9 \u2013 TABLE A & B&nbsp;\u2013 ASSEMBLY AND PARLIAMENTARY CONSTITUENCIES AND THEIR EXTENT\n| accessdate = 2005-05-31\n| work = Kerala\n| publisher = DELIMITATION COMMISSION OF INDIA }}</ref>\nCurrent MLA is [[Mathew T. Thomas|Adv. Mathew T Thomas]].\nCurrent MP [[Pathanamthitta (Lok Sabha constituency)]] is [[Anto Antony]].\n\n== Culture & Heritage ==\nThe heritage of Thiruvalla is not restricted only to its temples and their activities but is very diverse, encompassing the religions of Hinduism, Islam and Christianity. Numerous churches co-exist with temples and there are a few well-known mosques as well in this small town. These religious spaces shape the culture of Thiruvalla in unique manners. The temples were not only the places of worship but also played an integral role in shaping the revenue and trade models of the society. Thiruvalla boasts numerous temple performances and rituals which are unique only to this place which include Ammankudam, Arattu, Chandanakudam, Chuttuvilakku, Ezhunnallathu and a lot more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nativeplanet.com/thiruvalla/#overview|title=Thiruvalla|last=|first=|date=|website=Native Planet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n==Educational Institutions==\n* Pushpagiri Medical College\n* Mar Thoma College, Kuttapuzha\n* [[Titus II Teachers College, Thiruvalla]]\n* Mar Athanasios College for Advanced Studies (MACFAST)\n* SCS Higher Secondary School\n* MGM Higher Secondary School\n* DB Higher Secondary School \n* St.Thomas Higher secondary School\n* St.Mary's Residential Public School\n* Christ Central School\n* Believers Church School\n\n==Religion==\nThe city inside the modern municipal limits has comparable number of Hindus (46.92%) and Christians (48.03%). Muslims form 4.80% of the population.<ref>[http://www.census2011.co.in/data/town/803303-thiruvalla-kerala.html Census of India \u2013 Thiruvalla City population Religion data]</ref> The historic Paliakara St. George Orthodox Church, known for its exotic murals is in Thiruvalla.\nMajority of Christian population in Thiruvalla belongs to [[Malankara Orthodox]] community.\n\nThe headquarters of [[Malankara Marthoma Syrian Church]], headed by His Grace [[Joseph Mar Thoma]], is at Thiruvalla. The world famous [[Maramon Convention]] <ref>https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maramon_Convention</ref> is conducted, by [[Marthoma Syrian Church]], at [[Maramon]],Thiruvalla, every year.\n\nThe Headquarters of India's Largest Pentecostal denomination is in Kumbanad,Thiruvalla. \n\nThis is also home to the [[Sree Vallabha Temple]], the only one of its kind in the State to have Kathakali performed as a ritual offering every night.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.keralatourism.org/destination/thiruvalla-pathanamthitta/49|title=Thiruvalla Town|last=|first=|date=|website=keralatourism.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 January 2020}}</ref> St. Thomas Evangelical Church is one of several groups of [[Saint Thomas Christians]] tracing their origins to [[Thomas (Apostle)#Thomas%20and%20India|St. Thomas the Apostle]] who, according to [[sacred tradition]], came to India in AD 52. While STECI is considered to be an [[Episcopal polity|episcopal]] church, it is at the same time deeply influenced by [[Evangelicalism]].\n\n== Tourism ==\nThiruvalla attracts tourists and worshipers from all over the nation as the legendary \u2018Sri Vallabha Temple\u2019 also known as the, \u2018Southern Tirupati\u2019, is located here. This place is also a home to the Paliakkara Church with a history that takes you back to 52 AD, when Christianity was first introduced in Kerala. Thiruvalla has many stories and legends kept in its cultural folds. There is a story behind everything associated with this place, be it the temples, festivals or even its name. Story goes that during the reign of the Thiruvathamkoor Maharaja this place was known as Sri Vallabhapuram and later changed to Thiruvallabhapuram and it has evolved as Thiruvalla in recent times. There is another belief that the name Thiruvalla is named after the deity Thiru Vallabhan or Vishnu. Thiruvalla is thus also known as a town of Vishnu.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nativeplanet.com/thiruvalla/#overview|title=Thiruvalla|last=|first=|date=|website=native planet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Food ==\nPaddy is the major crop grown here and one can see the fields spread over stretches. Rice is the chief food item of Thiruvalla, naturally, as it is grown in abundance here. Contrary to the belief that South Indian food does comprise only of Idly and Dosa, you can sample and savour a host of other delicacies such as Puttu with plantain or black channa curry , kappa (tapioca)and fish curry and Appam or pancakes.{{fact|date=February 2020}} The meals are very heavy as a Kerala preparation can never be complete without coconut.{{fact|date=February 2020}} The locals here have a penchant of pickling foods like raw mangoes, lime or even gooseberries.{{fact|date=February 2020}}\n\n==Media==\nThiruvalla is headquarters for two Malayalam satellite channels which cater to Christian Devotional content, Power Vision and [[Athmeeya Yathra]].\n\nRadio Macfast 90.4 is an FM Station managed by the [[Mar Athanasios College for Advanced Studies, Thiruvalla|Mar Athanasios College for Advanced Studies]], in Thiruvalla.\n\n== Sports ==\nThe popular sports in Thiruvalla are the football and cricket. The football history of Thiruvalla can be traced back to the legendary footballer from Thiruvalla, [[Thomas Varghes]]e, called \"Tiruvalla Pappan\". He represented India in the London Olympics of 1948, and is described as one of the best defenders of 40's \u2013 50's from India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/This-Tiruvalla-Defender-Stood-Like-a-Wall-in-London-Olympics/2013/12/17/article1949601.ece|title=This Tiruvalla Defender Stood Like a Wall in London Olympics|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref> Today, Thiruvalla hosts many district and state level football and cricket tournaments. There is a stadium in Thiruvalla maintained by the Thiruvalla Municipal Council. This is the venue for most of the tournaments. It is also called \"Prithi stadium\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Kerala/Grounds/1245.html|title=Untitled Document|website=cricketarchive.com|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Indoor Cricket ===\nThe [[Kerala Cricket Association]] has set up the world class indoor cricket stadium complex in Thiruvalla, with world class facilities, with 24-7 practising facility. The facility is adjacent to the Thiruvalla Municipal stadium, and is constructed on 8000 square feet, on 50 cents of land. The facility also houses a library, multi-gym, board room, KCA district office, and a conference hall. Specially made natural grass wicket is the speciality of the practising nets in the courtyard. This indoor cricket facility is perhaps, the first of its kind in the state.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/worldclass-indoor-cricket-facility-for-thiruvalla/article7631576.ece|title=World-class indoor cricket facility for Thiruvalla|date=2015-09-09|newspaper=The Hindu|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref>\n\n==Notable persons==\n*[[Shalini]], Actress\n* [[Sreeja Chandran]], Actress \n* [[Abraham Kovoor]], hypnotherapist and [[wikt:rationalist|rationalist]]\n* [[Abu Abraham]], cartoonist\n* [[Madathilparampil Mammen Thomas#Works on M.M. Thomas|Dr. M.M. Thomas]], former Governor of Nagaland\n* [[Babu Thiruvalla]], movie director and producer\n*Pastor K C John (Former General Secretary of India Pentecostal Church of God)\n*Pastor K E Abraham(First President of Indian Pentecostal Church of God)\n* [[Baselios MarThoma Didymos I|Baselios Marthoma Didymos I]], [[Malankara Metropolitan]] and Catholicos of [[Malankara Orthodox Syrian Church]]\n* [[Blessy]] (Blessy Iype Thomas), movie director\n* [[ SANO KURIYAN ]] social worker \n* [[C. K. Ra]], artist\n* [[C.P. Mathen]] (1890\u20131960), banker and founder of the Quilon Bank\n* [[Chippy (actress)|Chippy]], movie actress\n* [[John Abraham (director)|John Abraham]], movie director\n* [[K. G. George]], movie director\n* [[Kakkanadan]], novelist and writer\n* [[Kaveri (actress)|Kaveri]], movie actress\n* [[Kaviyoor Ponnamma]], movie actress\n* [[M. G. Soman]], movie actor\n* [[Mathew T. Thomas]], Indian politician,\n* [[Meera Jasmine]] (Jasmine Mary Joseph), movie actress\n* [[Nadhiya|Nadiya Moythu]], movie actress\n* [[Nayantara]] (Diana Mariam Kurien, Kodiyattu), movie actress\n* [[Parvathy Jayaram|Parvathy]] (Ashwathy Kurup), movie actress\n* [[Sajeev John]] Physicist<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kochi/Tiruvallas-Sajeev-John-misses-the-Nobel-again/articleshow/10239177.cms|title=Tiruvalla's Sajeev John misses the Nobel again \u2013 Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2018-12-25}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Edathua]]\n* [[Thakazhy]]\n* [[Mavelikara]]\n* [[Chengannur]]\n* [[Changanassery]]\n* [[Kizhakkenmuthoor]]\n*[[Kozhencherry]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Thiruvalla}}\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Thiruvalla\n|North     = [[Changanassery]]\n|Northeast = [[Mallapally]]\n|East      = [[Pullad]]\n|Southeast = [[Kozhencherry]]\n|South     = [[Chengannur]]\n|Southwest = [[Mavelikkara]]\n|West      = [[Mannar, India|Mannar]],\n|Northwest = [[Edathua]]\n}}\n<!--Templates-->\n\n{{kerala|show=show}}\n{{Municipalities of Kerala|show=show}}\n{{Central Travancore}}\n{{Pathanamthitta district}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Pathanamthitta district]]\n[[Category:Thiruvalla| ]]\n", "text_old": "\n\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2015}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=October 2015}}\n<!-- See [[Wikipedia:WikiProject Indian cities]] for details -->\n{{Infobox settlement\n| name                            = Thiruvalla\n| native_name                     = <!-- Please do not add any Indic script in this infobox, per WP:INDICSCRIPT policy. -->\n| settlement_type                 = Town \n| image_skyline                   = Thiruvalla Bus Terminal Complex.jpg\n| image_alt                       =\n| image_caption                   = Thiruvalla KSRTC Bus Terminal\n| pushpin_map                     = India Kerala\n| pushpin_label_position          = right\n| pushpin_map_alt                 =\n| pushpin_map_caption             = Location in Kerala, India\n| subdivision_type                = Country\n| subdivision_name                = {{flag|India}}\n| subdivision_type1               = [[States and territories of India|State]]\n| subdivision_type2               = [[List of districts of India|District]]\n| subdivision_name1               = [[Kerala]]\n| subdivision_name2               = [[Pathanamthitta district|Pathanamthitta]]\n| established_title               = <!-- Established -->\n| established_date                =\n| founder                         =\n| named_for                       =\n| government_type                 =\n| governing_body                  =\n| unit_pref                       = Metric\n| area_footnotes                  =\n| area_total_km2                  =\n| area_rank                       =\n| elevation_footnotes             =\n| elevation_m                     =\n| population_total                = 52,883\n| population_as_of                = 2011\n| population_footnotes            = <ref>http://www.censusindia.gov.in/pca/SearchDetails.aspx?Id=676380</ref>\n| population_density_km2          = auto\n| population_rank                 =\n| population_demonym              =\n| demographics_type1              = Languages\n| demographics1_title1            = Official\n| timezone1                       = [[Indian Standard Time|IST]]\n| utc_offset1                     = +5:30\n| postal_code_type                = [[Postal Index Number|PIN]]\n| postal_code                     = 689101\n| area_code                       = 91-469\n| area_code_type                  = Telephone code\n| registration_plate              = KL-27\n| website                         = {{URL|https://www.thiruvalla.org.in}}\n| footnotes                       =\n| demographics1_info1             = [[Malayalam language|Malayalam]], [[English language|English]]\nLiteracy                  = 98.5%\n| blank2_name_sec2                = Nearest Airport\n| blank2_info_sec2                = [[Cochin International Airport Limited]]\n| official_name                   =\n}}\n\n'''Thiruvalla''', alternately spelled '''Tiruvalla''', is a small town and also the headquarters of the [[Thiruvalla taluk|Taluk of same name]] located in [[Pathanamthitta district]] in the State of [[Kerala]], [[India]]. The town is spread over an area of 27.94&nbsp;km&nbsp;.  It lies on the banks of the rivers [[Manimala River|Manimala]] and [[Pamba River|Pamba]], and is a land-locked region surrounded by irrigating streams and rivers.\n\nThiruvalla is regarded as the \"Land of Non resident Indians \".<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/efforts-on-to-give-facelift-to-thiruvalla/article7998777.ece|title=Efforts on to give facelift to Thiruvalla|date=2015-12-17|newspaper=The Hindu|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref> Thiruvalla is also famous for the dance of Kathakali, which is hosted in the Sreevallabha temple almost everyday in an year.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-kerala/where-kathakali-is-a-daily-affair/article3088714.ece|title=Where Kathakali is a daily affair|date=2006-08-11|work=The Hindu|access-date=2018-08-25|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref>\n\n==Demographics==\nThe town spans a geographic area of 27.94&nbsp;km\u00b2 with a population of 56,828 as of 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20040616075334/http://www.censusindia.net/results/town.php?stad=A&state5=999|archivedate=2004-06-16|title= Census of India 2001: Data from the 2001 Census, including cities, villages and towns  (Provisional)|accessdate=2008-11-01|publisher= Census Commission of India}}</ref> Males constitute 48% of the population and females 52%. In Thiruvalla, 10% of the population is under 6 years of age. Thiruvalla has a large [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|Non-Resident Indian Community]].\n\n== Etymology ==\nOld tradition tells that the name Thiruvalla comes from the word \"''Valla Vaay''\", named after the river Manimala which was known as ''Vallay\u0101r'' in ancient times. Before roads were developed,Thiruvalla village developed at the mouth of river Vallayar,connected far and near places through waterways, hence known as ''Valla v\u0101i''(v\u0101y in old Malayalam means mouth of river).<ref name=\":0\" /> Later the Dravidian Prefix 'Thiru (means holy /revered) attached to it and became Thiruvalla.\n\nAt the time of Aryan migration to south India it became one of the 64 Brahmin settlements. They correlated the name to \"Sree Vallabha\" means Husband of Lakshmi Devi. Sree Vallabha is the presiding deity of the Thiruvalla Temple and argues that shreevallabha Puram (Land of Vallabhan) became Thiruvalla.<ref name=\":0\" /> Thiruvalla as per the Sanskrit work \"\u0936\u094d\u0930\u0940\u0935\u0932\u094d\u0932\u092d \u0915\u094d\u0937\u0947\u0924\u094d\u0930 \u092e\u093e\u0939\u093e\u0924\u094d\u092e\u094d\u092f\u092e\u094d\" (\u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40\u0d35\u0d32\u0d4d\u0d32\u0d2d \u0d15\u0d4d\u0d37\u0d47\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d30 \u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d39\u0d3e\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d2e\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d02) (\u015br\u012bvallabha k\u1e63\u0113tra m\u0101h\u0101tmya\u1e41) is \"\u0936\u094d\u0930\u0940\u0935\u0932\u094d\u0932\u092d\u092a\u0941\u0930\u092e\u094d\" (\u0d36\u0d4d\u0d30\u0d40\u0d35\u0d32\u0d4d\u0d32\u0d2d\u0d2a\u0d41\u0d30\u0d02)(\u015br\u012bvallabhapura\u1e41). The work is said to be of 10th century CE.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n== Geography and Climate ==\nThiruvalla lies at an altitude of 21 m above sea level, on the basin of the rivers [[Pamba River|Pamba]] and [[Manimala River|Manimala]]. Thiruvalla is dotted with several natural canal streams (called \"thodu\" in Malayalam) like Chanthathodu, Manippuzha, Mullelithodu, and several others. The city area has riverine alluvial soil, and eastern parts have a laterite loam kind of soil classified under \"Southern Midlands\" agro-ecological zone, while the western suburbs like Niranam have a more sandy type of soil that resembles beaches. (Kuttanad agro-ecological zone)<ref name=\":2\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.kissankerala.net/kissan/kissancontents/soil.jsp#admin|title=KISSAN \u2013 Kerala|website=www.kissankerala.net|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref> The reason for this is believed to be the older status of Niranam as a port, before reclamation of Kuttanad from sea occurred. The Upper Kuttanad region in Thiruvalla has the \"Karappadam\" type of soil, which is clay loam in texture, has high organic matter, and is situated in areas about 1\u20132 m above sea level.<ref name=\":2\" />\n\nThe climate of Thiruvalla is classified as [[Tropical climate|tropical]]. There is significant rainfall in most months of the year. The short dry season has little effect on the overall climate. The K\u00f6ppen-Geiger climate classification is Am. The temperature here averages 27.3&nbsp;\u00b0C. In a year, the average rainfall is 2975&nbsp;mm.<ref name=\":3\">{{Cite web|url=http://en.climate-data.org/location/59916/|title=Climate: Thiruvalla - Climate graph, Temperature graph, Climate table - Climate-Data.org|website=en.climate-data.org|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref>\n\n{{Weather box|location=Thiruvalla|metric first=yes|single line=yes|Jan high C=31.3|Feb high C=31.7|Mar high C=32.7|Apr high C=32.7|May high C=32|Jun high C=29.8|Jul high C=29.8|Aug high C=29.8|Sep high C=30|Oct high C=30|Nov high C=30|Dec high C=30.7|Jan low C=22.5|Feb low C=23.4|Mar low C=24.7|Apr low C=25.4|May low C=25|Jun low C=23.9|Jul low C=23.9|Aug low C=23.8|Sep low C=24|Oct low C=23.8|Nov low C=23.5|Dec low C=22.6|Jan precipitation mm=22|Feb precipitation mm=35|Mar precipitation mm=60|Apr precipitation mm=155|May precipitation mm=320|Jun precipitation mm=596|Jul precipitation mm=542|Aug precipitation mm=372|Sep precipitation mm=284|Oct precipitation mm=326|Nov precipitation mm=210|Dec precipitation mm=54|source=http://en.climate-data.org/location/59916|date=}}\n\nAt an average temperature of 29.0&nbsp;\u00b0C, April is the hottest month of the year. July has the lowest average temperature of the year. It is 26.4&nbsp;\u00b0C. Between the driest and wettest months, the difference in precipitation is 574&nbsp;mm. Precipitation is the lowest in January, with an average of 22&nbsp;mm. With an average of 596&nbsp;mm, the most precipitation falls in June.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nDue to proximity to the equator, Thiruvalla has very less variation in average temperature. During the year, the average temperatures vary by 2.6&nbsp;\u00b0C.<ref name=\":3\" />\n\nThiruvalla is best known for its pleasant and welcoming weather. South West Monsoon winds bring heavy showers to Thiruvalla in the months of August for a couple of months. Thiruvalla has a distinctively tropical, yet pleasing climate. The best time to visit this historical town is after the rains as the healthy showers of monsoon leave this place lush green and pristine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nativeplanet.com/thiruvalla/#overview|title=Thiruvalla|last=|first=|date=|website=native planet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n==History==\n''This article is primarily about the history of the settlements in areas of present city around the temple, known historically as Thiruvalla. For the history of the places in Thiruvalla, also refer : [[Niranam|History of Niranam]], [[Koipuram|History of Koipuram]], [[Kumbanad|History of Kumbanad]], [[Kavumbhagom|History of Kavumbhagom]].''\n\n=== Ancient period ===\nThere is plenty of evidence to suggest that the area had been inhabited since 500 BCE, although an organized settlement was only founded around 800 CE.  The present day areas of [[Niranam]], and Kadapra on the western part of Thiruvalla were submerged under the sea before then.<ref name=\":0\" /> It is one of the 64 ancient ''brahmana graamams''.\n\nStone axes have been reported from Thiruvalla, belonging to Neolithic Age.<ref>\"Indus Civilisation and Tamil Language \u2013 Part 03\", page 34.\n\nhttp://210.212.62.26/pdf_files/books/Indus%20civilization%20and%20tamil%20language%20part%20003.pdf\n</ref> Thiruvalla has many Neolithic remains and got civilized earlier. The Aryan culture presented Thiruvalla as one of the 64 Brahmin settlements of Kerala, and one of the important too. Ptolemy mentions the Baris river, the present \"Pamba\" river.<ref name=\":1\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=FVsw35oEBv4C|title=A Survey Of Kerala History|last=Menon|first=A. Sreedhara|date=2007-01-01|publisher=DC Books|isbn=9788126415786|language=en}}</ref>\n\nThiruvalla was also an important commercial centre with the [[Niranam]] port in olden days, which is described by Pliny as \"[[Nelcynda]]\".<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SXMaAAAAMAAJ|title=Bulletin of the John Rylands Library|last=Library|first=John Rylands|date=1967-01-01|publisher=Kraus Reprint|language=en}}</ref> At this light, the \"Bacare\" could have been modern \"[[Purakkad]]\". The fact that modern western Thiruvalla contains the coastal kind of sand, and several sea shells in the soil despite being land locked proves that prior to the reclamation of Kuttanad from sea, Niranam and the whole western Thiruvalla could have been a coastal area.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\n=== The Growth to Feudalism ===\nUp to the beginning of the 10th century CE, Ays were the dominant powers in Kerala. The Ay kings ruled from Thiruvalla in North to Nagercoil in South. Ptolemy mentions this as from Baris ([[Pamba River|Pamba river]]) to Cape Comorin \"Aioi\" ([[Kanyakumari]]).<ref name=\":1\" /> By 12th century, we get the picture from the Thiruvalla copper plates, which are voluminous records that centre around the social life around the temple.<ref name=\":1\"/> The society The Thiruvalla temple had a large Vedic learning school (actually comparable to modern university) (\"Thiruvalla salai\"), which was one of the foremost learning centres<ref name=\"Cultural Heritage of Kerala\">{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=R7QNGkZKc5wC|title=Cultural Heritage of Kerala|date=2008-01-01|publisher=D.C. Books|isbn=9788126419036|language=en}}</ref> in Kerala. The Thiruvalla salai was one of the richest among the Vedic schools of Kerala, and according to the copper plates, the pupils of the school were fed with 350 nazhis of paddy everyday,<ref name=\"Cultural Heritage of Kerala\"/> which shows the vastness of its student population. Thiruvalla held a very eminent position among the spiritual and educational centres in ancient times.The Sri Vallabha Temple was one of the wealthiest temples of ancient Kerala, as is evident from the inscriptions in the plates. The part of the temple land required to 'feed the Brahmins' required 2.1 million litres of rice seeds, and for the \"maintenance of the eternal lamps\" required more than 340,000 litres of paddy seed capacity.<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=rNKGAwAAQBAJ|title=A Passage to Infinity: Medieval Indian Mathematics from Kerala and Its Impact|last=Joseph|first=George Gheverghese|date=2009-12-10|publisher=SAGE Publications India|isbn=9788132104810|language=en}}</ref> Due to the length, the antiquity and the nature of the language, Thiruvalla copper plates form the \"First book in Malayalam\", according to Prof. [[Elamkulam Kunjan Pillai|Elamkulam]].<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=_B7jAAAAMAAJ|title=Proceedings of the Indian History Congress|last=Congress|first=Indian History|date=1970-01-01|language=en}}</ref>\n\n=== Medieval period ===\n[[File:Syrian copper plates - Kollam (c. 883 AD).jpg|thumb|Thiruvalla copper plates]]\nThe rulers of Thiruvalla now belonged to the Thekkumkoor Dynasty, which had one of its headquarters at Idathil near Kaavil Temple. Idathil (Vempolinadu Edathil Karthavu)<ref>P. Shungoonny Menon, ''A history of Travancore'' (first edition: 1878, new edition: 1983), page 130 and 131, {{ISBN|978-81-7020-040-6}}</ref> was the family name of the Thekkumkoor kings. Today's Paliakara Palace is a branch of Lakshmipuram Palace of [[Changanacherry]], which is a branch of Alikottu Kovilakam of Pazhancherry in [[Malabar (Northern Kerala)|Malabar]]. Similarly, [[Nedumpuram Palace]] is a branch of Mavelikkara Palace is an heir to the [[Kolathiri]] tradition of Udayamangalam. The Thekkumkoor kings lost their control in the course of time and Vilakkili  (\u0d35\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d3f) Nampoothiris were rulers in 1752\u201353 when [[Marthanda Varma|Anizham Thirunal Marthanda Varma]], the king of [[Travancore]], seized it in a bloody battle in which the ruler was killed, though some dispute it, saying the surrender was peaceful as the Namboothiris were not naive to challenge the mighty army of [[Ramayyan Dalawa|Ramayyan]], the shrewd and sadistic Dalava (\u0d26\u0d33\u0d35)- head of administration and advisor \u2013 of Travancore.<ref name=\":0\">Shree Vallabha Mahakshethra Charitham, P. Unnikrishnan Nair</ref>\n\n==Politics==\nThe current Chairperson of the Municipality is Cherian Polachirackal and the Vice Chairman is Sreerenjini S Pillai for 2018\u20132020.<ref>{{cite web |title=Council |url=http://www.thiruvallamunicipality.in/council |publisher=Thiruvalla Municipality |accessdate=29 October 2018}}</ref>\n\nThiruvalla's assembly constituency is the part of the newly formed [[Pathanamthitta (Lok Sabha constituency)]].<ref>{{cite web\n| url = http://www.delimitation-india.com/Final_Publications/KERALA/Final_Order_Kerala.pdf\n|format=PDF| title = ORDER NO. 9 \u2013 TABLE A & B&nbsp;\u2013 ASSEMBLY AND PARLIAMENTARY CONSTITUENCIES AND THEIR EXTENT\n| accessdate = 2005-05-31\n| work = Kerala\n| publisher = DELIMITATION COMMISSION OF INDIA }}</ref>\nCurrent MLA is [[Mathew T. Thomas|Adv. Mathew T Thomas]].\nCurrent MP [[Pathanamthitta (Lok Sabha constituency)]] is [[Anto Antony]].\n\n== Culture & Heritage ==\nThe heritage of Thiruvalla is not restricted only to its temples and their activities but is very diverse, encompassing the religions of Hinduism, Islam and Christianity. Numerous churches co-exist with temples and there are a few well-known mosques as well in this small town. These religious spaces shape the culture of Thiruvalla in unique manners. The temples were not only the places of worship but also played an integral role in shaping the revenue and trade models of the society. Thiruvalla boasts numerous temple performances and rituals which are unique only to this place which include Ammankudam, Arattu, Chandanakudam, Chuttuvilakku, Ezhunnallathu and a lot more.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nativeplanet.com/thiruvalla/#overview|title=Thiruvalla|last=|first=|date=|website=Native Planet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n==Educational Institutions==\n* Pushpagiri Medical College\n* Mar Thoma College, Kuttapuzha\n* [[Titus II Teachers College, Thiruvalla]]\n* Mar Athanasios College for Advanced Studies (MACFAST)\n* SCS Higher Secondary School\n* MGM Higher Secondary School\n* DB Higher Secondary School \n* St.Thomas Higher secondary School\n\n==Religion==\nThe city inside the modern municipal limits has comparable number of Hindus (46.92%) and Christians (48.03%). Muslims form 4.80% of the population.<ref>[http://www.census2011.co.in/data/town/803303-thiruvalla-kerala.html Census of India \u2013 Thiruvalla City population Religion data]</ref> The historic Paliakara St. George Orthodox Church, known for its exotic murals is in Thiruvalla.\nMajority of Christian population in Thiruvalla belongs to [[Malankara Orthodox]] community.\n\nThe headquarters of [[Malankara Marthoma Syrian Church]], headed by His Grace [[Joseph Mar Thoma]], is at Thiruvalla. The world famous [[Maramon Convention]] <ref>https://en.m.wikipedia.org/wiki/Maramon_Convention</ref> is conducted, by [[Marthoma Syrian Church]], at [[Maramon]],Thiruvalla, every year.\n\nThe Headquarters of India's Largest Pentecostal denomination is in Kumbanad,Thiruvalla. \n\nThis is also home to the [[Sree Vallabha Temple]], the only one of its kind in the State to have Kathakali performed as a ritual offering every night.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.keralatourism.org/destination/thiruvalla-pathanamthitta/49|title=Thiruvalla Town|last=|first=|date=|website=keralatourism.org|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 January 2020}}</ref> St. Thomas Evangelical Church is one of several groups of [[Saint Thomas Christians]] tracing their origins to [[Thomas (Apostle)#Thomas%20and%20India|St. Thomas the Apostle]] who, according to [[sacred tradition]], came to India in AD 52. While STECI is considered to be an [[Episcopal polity|episcopal]] church, it is at the same time deeply influenced by [[Evangelicalism]].\n\n== Tourism ==\nThiruvalla attracts tourists and worshipers from all over the nation as the legendary \u2018Sri Vallabha Temple\u2019 also known as the, \u2018Southern Tirupati\u2019, is located here. This place is also a home to the Paliakkara Church with a history that takes you back to 52 AD, when Christianity was first introduced in Kerala. Thiruvalla has many stories and legends kept in its cultural folds. There is a story behind everything associated with this place, be it the temples, festivals or even its name. Story goes that during the reign of the Thiruvathamkoor Maharaja this place was known as Sri Vallabhapuram and later changed to Thiruvallabhapuram and it has evolved as Thiruvalla in recent times. There is another belief that the name Thiruvalla is named after the deity Thiru Vallabhan or Vishnu. Thiruvalla is thus also known as a town of Vishnu.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nativeplanet.com/thiruvalla/#overview|title=Thiruvalla|last=|first=|date=|website=native planet|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n\n== Food ==\nPaddy is the major crop grown here and one can see the fields spread over stretches. Rice is the chief food item of Thiruvalla, naturally, as it is grown in abundance here. Contrary to the belief that South Indian food does comprise only of Idly and Dosa, you can sample and savour a host of other delicacies such as Puttu with plantain or black channa curry , kappa (tapioca)and fish curry and Appam or pancakes.{{fact|date=February 2020}} The meals are very heavy as a Kerala preparation can never be complete without coconut.{{fact|date=February 2020}} The locals here have a penchant of pickling foods like raw mangoes, lime or even gooseberries.{{fact|date=February 2020}}\n\n==Media==\nThiruvalla is headquarters for two Malayalam satellite channels which cater to Christian Devotional content, Power Vision and [[Athmeeya Yathra]].\n\nRadio Macfast 90.4 is an FM Station managed by the [[Mar Athanasios College for Advanced Studies, Thiruvalla|Mar Athanasios College for Advanced Studies]], in Thiruvalla.\n\n== Sports ==\nThe popular sports in Thiruvalla are the football and cricket. The football history of Thiruvalla can be traced back to the legendary footballer from Thiruvalla, [[Thomas Varghes]]e, called \"Tiruvalla Pappan\". He represented India in the London Olympics of 1948, and is described as one of the best defenders of 40's \u2013 50's from India.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/kerala/This-Tiruvalla-Defender-Stood-Like-a-Wall-in-London-Olympics/2013/12/17/article1949601.ece|title=This Tiruvalla Defender Stood Like a Wall in London Olympics|website=The New Indian Express|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref> Today, Thiruvalla hosts many district and state level football and cricket tournaments. There is a stadium in Thiruvalla maintained by the Thiruvalla Municipal Council. This is the venue for most of the tournaments. It is also called \"Prithi stadium\".<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cricketarchive.com/Kerala/Grounds/1245.html|title=Untitled Document|website=cricketarchive.com|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref>\n\n=== Indoor Cricket ===\nThe [[Kerala Cricket Association]] has set up the world class indoor cricket stadium complex in Thiruvalla, with world class facilities, with 24-7 practising facility. The facility is adjacent to the Thiruvalla Municipal stadium, and is constructed on 8000 square feet, on 50 cents of land. The facility also houses a library, multi-gym, board room, KCA district office, and a conference hall. Specially made natural grass wicket is the speciality of the practising nets in the courtyard. This indoor cricket facility is perhaps, the first of its kind in the state.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/worldclass-indoor-cricket-facility-for-thiruvalla/article7631576.ece|title=World-class indoor cricket facility for Thiruvalla|date=2015-09-09|newspaper=The Hindu|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X|access-date=2016-03-20}}</ref>\n\n==Notable persons==\n*[[Shalini]], Actress\n* [[Sreeja Chandran]], Actress \n* [[Abraham Kovoor]], hypnotherapist and [[wikt:rationalist|rationalist]]\n* [[Abu Abraham]], cartoonist\n* [[Madathilparampil Mammen Thomas#Works on M.M. Thomas|Dr. M.M. Thomas]], former Governor of Nagaland\n* [[Babu Thiruvalla]], movie director and producer\n*Pastor K C John (Former General Secretary of India Pentecostal Church of God)\n*Pastor K E Abraham(First President of Indian Pentecostal Church of God)\n* [[Baselios MarThoma Didymos I|Baselios Marthoma Didymos I]], [[Malankara Metropolitan]] and Catholicos of [[Malankara Orthodox Syrian Church]]\n* [[Blessy]] (Blessy Iype Thomas), movie director\n* [[ SANO KURIYAN ]] social worker \n* [[C. K. Ra]], artist\n* [[C.P. Mathen]] (1890\u20131960), banker and founder of the Quilon Bank\n* [[Chippy (actress)|Chippy]], movie actress\n* [[John Abraham (director)|John Abraham]], movie director\n* [[K. G. George]], movie director\n* [[Kakkanadan]], novelist and writer\n* [[Kaveri (actress)|Kaveri]], movie actress\n* [[Kaviyoor Ponnamma]], movie actress\n* [[M. G. Soman]], movie actor\n* [[Mathew T. Thomas]], Indian politician,\n* [[Meera Jasmine]] (Jasmine Mary Joseph), movie actress\n* [[Nadhiya|Nadiya Moythu]], movie actress\n* [[Nayantara]] (Diana Mariam Kurien, Kodiyattu), movie actress\n* [[Parvathy Jayaram|Parvathy]] (Ashwathy Kurup), movie actress\n* [[Sajeev John]] Physicist<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/kochi/Tiruvallas-Sajeev-John-misses-the-Nobel-again/articleshow/10239177.cms|title=Tiruvalla's Sajeev John misses the Nobel again \u2013 Times of India|website=The Times of India|access-date=2018-12-25}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n* [[Edathua]]\n* [[Thakazhy]]\n* [[Mavelikara]]\n* [[Chengannur]]\n* [[Changanassery]]\n* [[Kizhakkenmuthoor]]\n*[[Kozhencherry]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Thiruvalla}}\n\n{{Geographic Location\n|Centre    = Thiruvalla\n|North     = [[Changanassery]]\n|Northeast = [[Mallapally]]\n|East      = [[Pullad]]\n|Southeast = [[Kozhencherry]]\n|South     = [[Chengannur]]\n|Southwest = [[Mavelikkara]]\n|West      = [[Mannar, India|Mannar]],\n|Northwest = [[Edathua]]\n}}\n<!--Templates-->\n\n{{kerala|show=show}}\n{{Municipalities of Kerala|show=show}}\n{{Central Travancore}}\n{{Pathanamthitta district}}\n\n[[Category:Cities and towns in Pathanamthitta district]]\n[[Category:Thiruvalla| ]]\n", "name_user": "61.1.216.227", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eEducational Institutions)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Thiruvalla"}
